<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36050g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36050g">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36050g"> 50(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hill of pleas</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Nor should we forget that this custom apparently preserved in Dublin <font color="green">[in the Akthing]</font> continued until recently in the Isle of Man, where the chief of the island or his representative sat under a canopy on the Thingwall mount with his &ldquo;doomsters&rdquo; or &ldquo;lawmen,&rdquo; the armed attendants standing around, and that a like custom long prevailed at the &ldquo;<mark>hill of pleas</mark>,&rdquo; the Thingmount of the Norwegian settlers in Ireland. <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD5" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD5"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 170</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
